into race acts and engendered new meanings for both. Koshy argues that the cultural work performed by narratives of white-Asian miscegenation dramatically transformed the landscape of desire in the United States, inventing new objects and relations of desire that established a powerful hold over U.S. culture, a capture of imaginative space that was out of all proportion to the actual numbers of Asian residents.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Asian American.2bisacsh1 aChang, Gordon H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362405440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503624054423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503624054/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles